      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican settlers faced numerous challenges including security threats, geographic isolation, and legal uncertainties. These hardships shaped community resilience and governance structures.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Frequent Native American raids threatened safety and property</li><li>Isolation and limited infrastructure complicated daily life</li><li>Legal disputes over land and water rights were common</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Settlers built fortified compounds and relied on militias to defend against raids, while negotiating water access with neighbors.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Discuss how these challenges might influence settlers’ decisions about where and how to live.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Underestimating the impact of legal and environmental challenges on settlement sustainability.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
