    "id": "slide20",
    "eyebrow": "Community Organization",
    "num": "08",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">08</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Community Organization</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Social and Political Structures in Texican Settlements</h2><ul><li>Local governance often centered on town councils (ayuntamientos)</li><li>Community defense relied on militias and volunteer groups</li><li>Religious institutions played a key role in social cohesion</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican communities organized themselves through local councils and militias, with churches serving as focal points for social and political life, reflecting Mexican colonial traditions adapted to frontier needs. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> An ayuntamiento would manage local disputes, organize defense, and oversee communal resources.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how these structures helped Texicans manage frontier challenges.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican communities lacked formal governance or defense mechanisms.</p></div></div>",
