      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican communities organized themselves through local councils and militias, with churches serving as focal points for social and political life, reflecting Mexican colonial traditions adapted to frontier needs.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; jinxschwartz.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Local governance often centered on town councils (ayuntamientos)</li><li>Community defense relied on militias and volunteer groups</li><li>Religious institutions played a key role in social cohesion</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>An ayuntamiento would manage local disputes, organize defense, and oversee communal resources.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze how these structures helped Texicans manage frontier challenges.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texican communities lacked formal governance or defense mechanisms.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; tshaonline.org; jinxschwartz.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p>"
