    "id": "slide26",
    "eyebrow": "Texican Cultural Identity",
    "num": "14",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">14</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Texican Cultural Identity</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Cultural Contributions of Texicans During Early Texas History</h2><ul><li>Texicans preserved Mexican cultural traditions while adapting to frontier life</li><li>They influenced language, religion, and customs in early Texas society</li><li>Their bicultural identity shaped Texas’s unique cultural landscape</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans maintained Mexican cultural practices such as Catholicism and Spanish language use, even as they adapted to the frontier environment. This bicultural identity contributed to the distinct cultural fabric of early Texas (s2, s7). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican communities celebrated traditional Mexican festivals alongside new Texan customs, blending cultural elements.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how Texican cultural identity influenced early Texas social life.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the persistence of Mexican cultural traditions among Texicans after independence.</p></div></div>",
