      "secnum": "Deep Dive 16",
      "h": "Interpreting Political Language in Texican Records",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Government records from Texican leaders often reveal their political aims and cultural identities, showing how they negotiated between Mexican rule and Texan independence (s2).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Examine language reflecting political goals and identity</li><li>Note references to Mexican and Texan affiliations</li><li>Identify expressions of loyalty or dissent</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A provisional government decree uses terms like 'Mexican citizens' and 'Texan rights' indicating dual identity.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Highlight phrases that show Texican political priorities in the document.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Reading documents without considering the political context of shifting sovereignty.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p>"
