    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">18</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Synthesizing Texican Perspectives</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Comparing Government Records and Personal Letters</h2><ul><li>Government records emphasize political strategy and public identity</li><li>Personal letters reveal private emotions and cultural concerns</li><li>Together, they provide a fuller picture of Texican experiences</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Analyzing both official documents and personal writings allows learners to understand the multifaceted nature of Texican identity and political roles during the revolution (s2, s7). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Contrasting a government decree’s formal tone with a letter’s emotional language highlights different facets of Texican life.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Compare how political and personal documents portray Texican loyalties.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Relying on a single source type, leading to incomplete understanding.</p></div></div>",
