    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">23</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Preparing for Document Analysis Workshop</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Key Concepts for Analyzing Texican Primary Sources</h2><ul><li>Understand the historical and political context of Mexican Texas</li><li>Recognize language indicating identity, loyalty, and bias</li><li>Use cross-referencing to validate interpretations</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Before the workshop, learners review essential concepts for critically analyzing Texican primary sources (s10, s11, s12). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Noting how terms like 'citizen' or 'rebel' carry political weight in documents.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> List questions to ask when analyzing a primary source document.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Failing to consider source bias or historical context.</p></div></div>",
