    "id": "slide38",
    "eyebrow": "Caddo Nation",
    "num": "26",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">26</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Caddo Nation</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">The Caddo: Agricultural Allies and Neighbors</h2><ul><li>The Caddo were settled agriculturalists with established villages</li><li>They engaged in trade and diplomacy with Texican settlers</li><li>Caddo social structure included confederacies and councils</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">The Caddo’s settled lifestyle and political organization allowed for relatively stable relations with Texicans, often involving trade and negotiated land use. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texicans exchanged livestock and tools for Caddo crops and crafted goods, fostering interdependence.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify benefits and challenges Texicans faced in maintaining peaceful relations with the Caddo.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Overlooking the Caddo’s political complexity and treating them as a single unified group.</p></div></div>",
