    "id": "slide40",
    "eyebrow": "Negotiation and Conflict",
    "num": "28",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">28</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Negotiation and Conflict</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Balancing Diplomacy and Defense on the Frontier</h2><ul><li>Texicans negotiated treaties to secure peace and trade rights</li><li>Conflicts arose over land, resources, and cultural misunderstandings</li><li>Both sides used diplomacy and force as circumstances dictated</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Frontier relations were fluid, with periods of cooperation interrupted by violent clashes, reflecting competing interests and cultural differences. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A treaty might grant Texicans access to hunting grounds in exchange for trade goods and peace pledges.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Debate the effectiveness of treaties versus military action in maintaining frontier stability.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming treaties were always honored or that conflict was inevitable.</p></div></div>",
