      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Reflection solidifies learning by connecting role-play experiences to historical complexities and multiple viewpoints.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Discuss successes and challenges experienced during role-play</li><li>Identify how historical context influenced decisions</li><li>Reflect on Native and Texican perspectives and motivations</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Learners note how mistrust limited agreement scope despite mutual benefits.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Write a brief summary comparing your role-play experience to historical accounts of Texican-Native relations.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Focusing only on winning the negotiation rather than understanding perspectives.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
