    "id": "slide46",
    "eyebrow": "Practice Checkpoint",
    "num": "34",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">34</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Practice Checkpoint</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Quiz: Texican and Native American Relations</h2><ul><li>Identify key characteristics of the Caddo and Comanche tribes</li><li>Explain the dual nature of Texican-Native interactions</li><li>Recognize challenges in interpreting historical sources</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">This quiz assesses understanding of the complex relationships and historiographical issues discussed. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Question: Which tribe was known for horse-mounted warfare? Answer: Comanche.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Complete the quiz to test your knowledge and identify areas for review.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Confusing tribe characteristics or oversimplifying interactions.</p></div><div id=\"quiz-slide46\" class=\"quizbox popquiz anim\" data-quiz=\"[{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;mc&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:2,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;What is the origin of the term &#39;Texican&#39;?&quot;,&quot;options&quot;:[&quot;It referred to Mexican settlers living in Texas during the early 1800s&quot;,&quot;It was a nickname for Anglo settlers after Texas became a republic&quot;,&quot;It described Native American tribes in Texas&quot;,&quot;It was a term for modern Texans&quot;],&quot;answer&quot;:0,&quot;why&quot;:&quot;The term &#39;Texican&#39; originally described Mexican settlers in Texas during the early 19th century, distinguishing them from Anglo settlers and later identities.&quot;},{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;sa&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:3,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Explain the role of Texicans in early Texas history and how their cultural background influenced their actions during the Texas Revolution.&quot;,&quot;rubric&quot;:&quot;Answer should identify Texicans as Mexican settlers in Texas, describe their cultural ties to Mexico, and explain their complex loyalties and contributions during the Texas Revolution, supported by examples from primary sources.&quot;,&quot;sample&quot;:&quot;Texicans were Mexican settlers in Texas who maintained cultural ties to Mexico but also adapted to frontier life. During the Texas Revolution, many Texicans had divided loyalties, with some supporting independence and others remaining loyal to Mexico. Their unique cultural background influenced their political and social roles in early Texas history.&quot;,&quot;accept&quot;:[&quot;Texicans were Mexican settlers in Texas with cultural ties to Mexico who played complex roles during the Texas Revolution&quot;,&quot;They had divided loyalties influenced by their Mexican heritage and frontier experiences&quot;,&quot;Texicans contributed politically and culturally to early Texas history with nuanced perspectives&quot;]}]\" data-pop=\"1\"></div></div>",
